comment: Oh, and Franco needs to "man up" and openly admit his involvement in manufacturing evidence to support Amber.  The judge should not have allowed his testimony to be "sealed" in order to protect his reputation.  He is an accomplice to a crime.  I recognize that prosecuting attorneys regularly negotiate with people who have committed a crime to forgo charges in exchange for their statement BUT, this is a far too public situation to show compromises of the law.  He is clearly being given preferential treatment due to his celebrity status and wealth.   Besides, we are talking about Franco.  He has a history of solicitation for sex with minors and he promotes drug use.  His reputation was already trash.  Yes, he would expose his actions but by providing truthful testimony he would actually improve his image.   If he continues to protect his self, allowing the accusations against Johnny to remain questionable when he knows they are false, it is one of the most cowardly things a man can do.
author: Sandi Hurd

comment: Thank you for taking the time to present this.  I hope Johnny is fully exonerated.  The media needs to accept their part in the pain and loss Johnny has endured.  This is also true of the people who publicly shamed him  and damaged his career, his image, his life.  The organizations who took advantage of the publicity to promote domestic violence prevention without any type of validation must acknowledge they failed.  Possibly they were simply overzealous but they need to accept they violated a critical element of domestic violence awareness, victim blaming.  They ALL have a DUTY to correct the damage they caused.  They hurt Johnny, they hurt their own reputation, they hurt every victim of domestic violence, and they hurt the innocent "bystanders".  In this case, Johnny's children.  Particularly his son who was bullied at school as a result.  What happened is not acceptable!  We need to hold them accountable.
